<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100221974091444></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100221974091444><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=6&mid=100221974091444>RE: Stats / Damage  Discussion: Caution - long post!</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=6&mid=100221974091444#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=600><span id=Guru>PraetorFenix</span></a>, <span id=Guru>Guru</span><br><span id=notbold>276 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Oct 4th 2:22 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.36]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>As my addition for those who haven't read it, here's a post I made about a year ago regarding specific damage calculations.&nbsp;&nbsp;In a few days this will all mean nothing and I get to recalculate everything, but for today's info:<br><br><br><br>Most younger paladins, and a lot of people still believe that damage/delay is the way to calculate weapon efficiency.  Not only is this 100% <b>wrong</b>, it is extremely misleading to people of other classes who will claim, "ur class roxX0rz cuz u have firey avengur."<br><br>The purpose of this post is to dispel any of those myths about damage calculation, so we can figure out exactly how we do damage.<br><br>Be forewarned that below level 27 or 28, these formulae are extremely inaccurate.  They are also slightly off at strength higher than 200-ish.<br><br>Get out your math degrees and enjoy :)<br><br>First, before you can calculate anything, you need to know two very simple formulae.  They are the forumlae to figure out the level bonus for one-handed and two-handed weapons.  These bonuses are the same for <b>every weapon of the same type at the same level</b>.  The damage bonus you get on that rusty short sword is the same one you're getting on that Halycon Broadsword.  The faster your weapon, the more often this damage is applied.  This is why Fiery Avenger is <b>not</b> the best weapon in the game (extremely long delay, thus the damage bonus gets applied less often).<br><br>This is how we calculate the level bonus:<br><br><i>1hLevelBonus = (Level - 25)/3<br><br>2hLevelBonus = (Level - 25)/1.80</i><br><br>Next, I'll show you how to calculate maximum damage.  This is one of the more complex formulae out there, so...  Be glad.<br><br><i>Maximum = ((WeaponSkill + Strength) / 100) * (WeaponDamage + LevelBonus)</i><br><br>Just a quick note, WeaponDamage is the damage number listed on the weapon.  This would be 33 for Fiery Avenger, 15 for Ghoulbane, or 6 for a Polished Granite Tomahawk.<br><br>This all seems pretty straightforward, right?  Now I need to explain something else.  Through lots of log parsing, a lot of us have found that there is a certain number (that we call the Magic Number) that you will hit for around 40 to 45 percent of the time, <b>totally disregarding strength</b>.  That's right.  Strength doesn't do jack to your damage other than maybe 0.5% more damage overall.  It only increases the amount of numbers that you'll hit, and it doesn't mean that you'll hit for those numbers a lot.  I'll debate this further down the road however in different posts should people wish to try and shoot down these claims. :)<br><br>To calculate the Magic Number (somtimes just called MN), you use this formula:<br><br><i>MagicNumber = 2*WeaponDamage + LevelBonus</i><br><br>This is the same for both one-handed and two-handed weapons, except for that you use the 1hLevelBonus I listed above for one-handers and the 2hLevelBonus for two-handers.<br><br>And now, we come down to minimum damage.  This is calculated in two different ways for one-handers and two-handers.<br><br>For one-handers, you calculate minimum damage like this:<br><br><i>Minimum = 1 + 1hLevelBonus</i><br><br>For two-handers, you calculate it like this:<br><br><i>Minimum = 3 + 2hLevelBonus</i><br><br>Are we catching up?  Pick your weapon that you use currently, and one that your friend uses currently.  Figure out everything about them that I've listed already, and then do the next section which I so lovingly title:<br><br><b>So how does this all fit into figuring out damage per second</b>?<br><br>It's another big old formula.  I'm getting tired of typing at this point, so I'll just give it to you:<br><br><i>AverageDamage = (0.45 * Minimum) + (0.45 * MagicNumber) + (0.1 * Maximum)</i><br><br>Okay, so now you've got your average damage per swing figured out.  Great!  Only one thing...  this doesn't let you compare weapons because they have different delays!<br><br>To calculate what I'm getting at (Damage/Second), we need just <b>two</b> more formulae to finish this up (are you getting excited too?).<br><br>The first we need is the Double Attack Formula.  It is calculated as this for <b>paladins</b>.  I am not sure if it will work for warriors, rangers, etc.  I'll probabally test it out someday.<br><br>Here is how we calculate Double Attack:<br><br><i>DoubleAttack% = (Skill + Level)/500</i><br><br>If I'm not mistaken, Double Attack caps off at 200 for all hybrids and warriors (not for monks and Rogues, those high-skill bastards), and increases at 5 skill points for every level (plus five for level one).  Would you like an extra formula for this?  <i>(Level + 1) * 5</i><br><br>For the final calculation, we'll assume that accuracy is 45-55% against even cons.<br><br>Damage Per Second is calculated as follows:<br><br><i>DPS = Accuracy% * (AverageDamage/(Delay/10)) *(1 + DoubleAttack%)</i><br><br>As far as I am concerned, this is as accurate as it gets.  If I wasn't so tired of typing this up, I'd post some sort of ending.  But I am, so have fun with your damage formulae, and don't make your head explode kids!<br><br>*Note:  These formulae will not work for weapons wielded in the offhand.  As this is a paladin board, dual wield predictions are excluded from this discussion.<br><br><i>(Edit 11/14/2000:  These formulae are slightly off for two handed weapons with delay lower than 28, and any weapon with a delay higher than 40.  Bear this in mind.)<br><br>(Edit: 06/28/2001:  These formulae don't apply post-50.  Doh!)<br><br>(Edit 09/12/2001:  Changed accuracy to more closely reflect our attack rating.)<br><br>(Edit 10/04/2001:  I have yet to find a reliable method of predicting damage with the Avatar buff up.  It appears to simply skew the damage more towards the max than the min, but it is quite a bit more complex than that.  Therefore if you have a Primal weapon or a good shaman friend, these formulae will again not be 100 percent accurate.)</i><br>&nbsp;<br><b>Praetor</b>, 60th Crusader<br>Avatars of Discord</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
